Summary:

  • New Gas Supply Agreement: 7-year deal with Greymouth Gas NZ Ltd (GGNZ) for up to 7PJ of gas annually, starting 1 October 2025 (extendable by 3 years).
  • Impact on Renewables: Expected to generate 200-300GWh/year of peaking electricity (98% renewable grid contribution) alongside hydro assets.
  • Strategic Rationale: Diversifies gas supply, supports NZ businesses transitioning from gas, and aligns with net-zero generation by 2035 goal.
  • Investment Context: Part of $2B+ renewable infrastructure investment over past 4 years.

(Note: No direct capital markets impact; operational/strategic update only.)

• Director Share Purchase: Hartley Atkinson (Director) increased holdings via Atkinson Family Trust by 200,000 AFT ordinary shares (on-market purchases, ~30 Jun – 2 Jul 2025).
  • Average Price: NZ$2.83/share (total ~NZ$566,000).
  • Total Holdings Post-Transaction: 72,259,496 shares (via trust) + 867,826 shares (direct/beneficial).

No other material information identified (transaction does not alter capital structure or liquidity materially).

Here’s the material information extracted from the ASX announcement, formatted concisely for capital markets purposes:

Operational & Financial Highlights (May 2025 Traffic Report)

  • Capacity Reduction: Group ASKs down 2.7% YoY (May 2025), driven by global engine maintenance delays.
  • Long Haul: -2.2%
  • Domestic: -5.5%
  • Short Haul Int’l: -2.2%.
  • Revenue Performance:
  • Group YTD underlying RASK +2.0% YoY (Long Haul +2.8%, Short Haul +0.4%).
  • Passenger Load Factor improved to 82.0% (May) vs. 79.5% YoY.
  • Key Metrics (YTD FY25 vs. FY24):
  • Passengers carried: -3.1% (14.5m).
  • Revenue Passenger Km: -1.3%.

Strategic & Market Updates (Media Releases)

  1. Capacity Expansion:
  2. Tasman/Pacific: 1.7m seats (Oct 2025–Mar 2026), +130K seats YoY; 8% more premium seats.
  3. North America: +34K seats (+8% YoY); 20.5K additional premium seats across long-haul routes.
  4. New Route: Christchurch–Adelaide (seasonal, 15K seats).
  5. Fleet Investment:
  6. 2 new A321neo aircraft (214 seats each), adding 70K annual seats to network.
  7. 7 retrofitted 787 Dreamliners entering service by 2025, boosting premium capacity.
  8. China Market Push:
  9. Partnership with Air China & Tourism NZ; $700K+ marketing investment to stimulate Chinese tourism (8% of NZ’s int’l visitors).

No capital raising, trading halt, or material liquidity/capital structure changes identified.

Priority Takeaway: Mixed operational trends (capacity constraints, higher RASK) offset by aggressive network/fleet expansion to capture premium demand. Asia/North America growth and cost-efficient fleet upgrades are key valuation drivers.

• FY25 uNPAT guidance: Expected at lower end of analyst range ($27.0M–$34.4M), citing weak global RV sales and USA market challenges.
  • Manufacturing decline: Australia/NZ divisions face lower earnings due to reduced production volumes.
  • FY26 outlook: Opening net debt ~$500M; strong rental revenue growth in NZ/AU (+25% YoY forward bookings).
  • USA market: Forward bookings initially dropped 40–50% post-Liberation Day but now near typical levels; single-digit YoY revenue decline expected.
  • Potential impairments: Preliminary assessment suggests possible NZ$36M goodwill impairment (USA business); other non-cash one-offs may impact statutory NPAT (no covenant effect).

Omitted: Operational initiatives (non-specific), historical context, director details.
